<div1 type="poem" id="d3"><pb n="616"/>
<head>
THE SLEEPING FLOWERS.<lb/>
BY EMILY DICKINSON.
</head>

<lg type="verse">

<l>"WHOSE are the little beds," I asked,
</l><l>"Which in the valleys lie?"
</l><l>Some shook their heads, and others smiled,
</l><l>And no one made reply.
</l></lg>

<lg type="stanza">
<l>Perhaps they did not hear, I said,
</l><l>I will inquire again.
</l><l>"Whose are the beds&mdash;the tiny beds
</l><l>So thick upon the plain?"
</l></lg>

<lg type="stanza">
<l>"'T is daisy in the shortest;
</l><l>A little further on,&mdash;
</l><l>Nearest the door, to wake the first,&mdash;
</l><l>Little leontodon.
</l></lg>

<lg type="stanza">
<l>"'T is iris, sir, and aster,
</l><l>Anemone and bell;
</l><l>Batschia in the blanket red,
</l><l>And chubby daffodil."
</l></lg>

<lg type="stanza">
<l>Meanwhile, at many cradles,
</l><l>She rocked and gently smiled,
</l><l>Humming the quaintest lullaby
</l><l>That ever soothed a child.
</l></lg>

<lg type="stanza">
<l>"Hush!  Epigea wakens!
</l><l>The crocus stirs her hood,&mdash;
</l><l>Rhodora's cheek is crimson,
</l><l>She's dreaming of the wood."
</l></lg>

<lg type="stanza">
<l>Then turning from them, reverent,
</l><l>"Their bedtime 't is," she said;
</l><l>"The bumblebees will wake them
</l><l>When April woods are red."
</l></lg>

</div1>
